responded to new challenges in theaftermath of the First Crusade in 1099. The Christian possession of Jerusalem questioned the legitimation of the papal cathedral in Rome as the summit of sacerdotal representation. To meet this challenge, what may be described astranslatio templi (the transfer of the temple) was used to strengthen the status of the Lateran. The Ark of the Covenant was central as part of the treasure from the Jerusalem temple, allegedly transported to Rome, and according to contemporary accounts depicted on the arch of Titus. The author explores the history of the Lateran Ark of the Covenant through a reading of the description of the Lateran Church (Descriptio Lateranensis Ecclesiae), composed around 1100. She follows the transmission of the text both in the Lateran Archive and in a monastic settings in northern France and Belgium, comparing the claim to the Ark with similar claims in texts from Jerusalem. The book also includes a new edition of the Descriptio and an English translation. EIVOR ANDERSEN OFTESTAD holds a PhD in Church History.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArk of the Covenant. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / General.2bisacsh  aArch of Titus.  aArk of the Covenant.  aDescriptio Lateranensis Ecclesiae.  aFirst Crusade.  aHistorical accounts.  aHoly Relics.  aJerusalem.  aLateran Church.  aLegitimation.  aTemple transfer.  aTradition.  aTranslatio templi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787444980?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787444980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787444980/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 